         <abstract>
            <p>The conventional approach to measuring mutual fund performance seems to imply that the funds going up the most in 1967-68 were the best, and the funds going down the most in 1969-70 were the worst. Unfortunately, numerous funds appeared on both lists. The performance of fund groups actually bears a highly consistent relationship to the action of the market, even though absolute performance of individual funds is not predictable.</p>
          </abstract>
